Evaluation¶
To evaluate the best treatment of missing values, we'll split our data into a train and test set.  WIth the train set we'll generate a model and measure the root mean squared error (RMSE) on the test set.  Models leading to smaller RMSE are considered superior to those with higher RMSE.  We make a several adjustments to a typical model building exercise to simplify and focus on handling missing data.  Examples include:


    

  • Scaling / Normalization of numerical features
    • 

  • Cross validation
    • 














In [109]:



    


resultsDF = pd.DataFrame(columns=['RMSE'])



    















Pipeline & Objective¶
For our pipeline, we're going to treat our categorical values and numeric values differently.  These functions allow us to select based on columns or column dtype.  We'll use that in a FeatureUnion which will handle taking different inputs, apply treatments and combine them into an array. (https://ramhiser.com/post/2018-04-16-building-scikit-learn-pipeline-with-pandas-dataframe/)













In [110]:



    


class ColumnSelector(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self, columns):
        self.columns = columns

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self

    def transform(self, X):
        assert isinstance(X, pd.DataFrame)

        try:
            return X[self.columns]
        except KeyError:
            cols_error = list(set(self.columns) - set(X.columns))
            raise KeyError("The DataFrame does not include the columns: %s" % cols_error)


class TypeSelector(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self, dtype):
        self.dtype = dtype

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self

    def transform(self, X):
        assert isinstance(X, pd.DataFrame)
        return X.select_dtypes(include=[self.dtype])



    















Data Removal¶
A trivial approach to missing data is to simply remove the missing rows / columns.  Column-wise deletion is viable when the majority of entries have missing data.  For example, a feature that is present in only 10-20% of rows.  There are downsides to data removal strategies.  First, you are reducing data that could otherwise be available for training.  This could affect your accuracy.  As well, removing row-wise data really hinges on the assumption that your missing values are missing completely at random (MCAR).  MCAR assumes that there is no relationship between the missing value and your dataset.  This assumption may be unlikely, where your data is missing at random (MAR).  With MAR, you have some conditional relationship between missing values and your data.  Row-wise deletion may be appropriate with MCAR and controlled for with MAR.  Column-wise deletion typically affects your feature set and possibly your predictive power.















Row Removal¶












In [111]:



    


removedRowDF = df.dropna()
print('Removed {} of {} ({:.2f}%)'.format(df.shape[0] - removedRowDF.shape[0], df.shape[0], 
                                         (df.shape[0] - removedRowDF.shape[0]) * 100.0 / df.shape[0]))
y = removedRowDF['Income']
X = removedRowDF.drop('Income', axis=1)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=1337)

ohe = OneHotEncoder(categories='auto') #OneHotEncoder(categorical_features=X.dtypes=='category')
clf = LinearRegression()
pipe = Pipeline(steps=[('ohe', ohe), ('regression', clf)])
pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)  

pred = pipe.predict(X_test)
rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, pred))
print('RMSE = {:.2f}'.format(rmse))
resultsDF.loc['Row Removal'] = [rmse]



    















    






Removed 2117 of 8993 (23.54%)
RMSE = 2007.24

Max Likelihood¶
With this technique we look to replace a missing value with the max likelihood of the column.  This is an intuitive guess that focuses on the values within a given column to make an estimated guess.  Our column's maximum likelihood will draw from a measure of central tendency (mean, mode, median).  This technique may be sufficient for some columns but can suffer when we have missing data that is not completely random and does not take into account correlations between the presence of missing values.


Numeric Features:


    

  • Mean
    • 

  • Median
    • 

  • Mode (Most Frequent)
    • 



Categorical Features:


    

  • Most Frequent
    • 

  • Constant (Indicator Level)
    • 
















SimpleImputer - Mean¶












In [114]:



    


y = df['Income']
X = df.drop('Income', axis=1)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=1337)

process = make_pipeline(
    FeatureUnion(transformer_list=[
        ("numeric_features", make_pipeline(
            TypeSelector(np.number),
            SimpleImputer(strategy="mean")
        )),
        ("categorical_features", make_pipeline(
            TypeSelector("category"),
            SimpleImputer(strategy="most_frequent"),
            OneHotEncoder(categories='auto')
        ))
    ])
)

clf = LinearRegression()
pipe = Pipeline(steps=[('process', process), ('regression', clf)])
pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)

pred = pipe.predict(X_test)
rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, pred))
print('RMSE = {:.2f}'.format(rmse))
resultsDF.loc['SimpleImputer Mean'] = [rmse]



    















    






RMSE = 2061.29

    FeatureUnion(transformer_list=[

    ])

Iterative Imputation¶
We use the IterativeImputer (which came from the Fancyimpute package).  Rather than MLE or dropping data, we attempt to fit a replacement of the missing value from an estimator.  We can choose from a range of estimators:


    

  • BayesRidge (Default Estimator)
    • 

  • K Nearest Neighbors 
    • 
















IterativeImputer - BayesRidge¶












In [120]:



    


y = df['Income']
X = df.drop('Income', axis=1)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=1337)

process = make_pipeline(
    FeatureUnion(transformer_list=[
        ("numeric_features", make_pipeline(
            TypeSelector(np.number),
            IterativeImputer(missing_values=np.nan)
        )),
        ("categorical_features", make_pipeline(
            TypeSelector("category"),
            SimpleImputer(strategy="constant", fill_value=0),
            OneHotEncoder(categories='auto')
        ))
    ])
)

clf = LinearRegression()
pipe = Pipeline(steps=[('process', process), ('regression', clf)])
pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)

pred = pipe.predict(X_test)
rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, pred))
print('RMSE = {:.2f}'.format(rmse))
resultsDF.loc['IterativeImputer BayesRidge'] = [rmse]



    















    






RMSE = 2060.27





















IterativeImputer - KNN¶












In [121]:



    


y = df['Income']
X = df.drop('Income', axis=1)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=1337)

est = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=5)

    FeatureUnion(transformer_list=[
        ("numeric_features", make_pipeline(

        ("categorical_features", make_pipeline(
            TypeSelector("category"),
            SimpleImputer(strategy="constant", fill_value=0),
            OneHotEncoder(categories='auto')
        ))
    ])
)

clf = LinearRegression()
pipe = Pipeline(steps=[('process', process), ('regression', clf)])
pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)

pred = pipe.predict(X_test)
rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, pred))
print('RMSE = {:.2f}'.format(rmse))

Missing Capable Models¶














XGBoost - NaN¶












In [129]:



    


y = df['Income']
X = df.drop('Income', axis=1)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=1337)

process = make_pipeline(
    FeatureUnion(transformer_list=[
        ("numeric_features", make_pipeline(
            TypeSelector(np.number),
            SimpleImputer(strategy="constant", fill_value=-1)
        )),
        ("categorical_features", make_pipeline(
            TypeSelector("category"),
            SimpleImputer(strategy="constant", fill_value=-1),
            OneHotEncoder(categories='auto')
        ))
    ])
)

clf = xgb.XGBRegressor(objective="reg:linear", missing=-1, random_state=42)
pipe = Pipeline(steps=[('process', process), ('regression', clf)])
pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)

pred = pipe.predict(X_test)
rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, pred))
print('RMSE = {:.2f}'.format(rmse))
resultsDF.loc['XGBoost NaN'] = [rmse]



    















    






RMSE = 1959.61

            SimpleImputer(strategy="mean")

clf = xgb.XGBRegressor(objective="reg:linear", random_state=42)

rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, pred))
print('RMSE = {:.2f}'.format(rmse))

Summary¶
Overall:


    

  • Pandas-profiling is a good addition for EDA & has missing plots
    • 

  • Our main strategies for dealing with missing values includes:
      

    • Removing missing rows / columns
      • 

    • Handling missing with Max Likelihood
      • 

    • Handling missing with Iterative Imputation 
      • 

    • Using a model capable of intrinsicly handling missing (XGBoost - Tree Split)
      • 

    

    • 

  • Feature Unions allow us to have multiple pre-processing paths
    • 



For results on this dataset:


    

  • Imputing values for XGBoost beat missing treatment
    • 

  • Row Removal beat Imputation, but can't handle Missing Data for prediction
    • 

  • Best Imputation strategy was applying Mean for Numerical and a Constant level for Catgegorical (i.e. Missing)
    •
